Old High German <i>glou</i> ‘sharp witted’ + <i>hart</i> ‘strong’.","Flemish <b>Clauwaert</b>, a derivative of Dutch <i>klauw</i> ‘claw’ (referring to the heraldic claw of a lion), denoting a member of the medieval militia from Gent."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Julienne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Julian  , now also found in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Julienne Cloward was born in 1350, in Warwick, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Henry Cloward, was 20 and her mother, Lady Julia Henry, was 20. She married Henry Alexander Thomas de Richmond Webb in 1371, in Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1410, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1350–1410":"1350–1410","1350–1397":"1350–1397","1372–1425":"1372–1425","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1382–1458":"1382–1458","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1330–1410":"1330–1410","1458":"1458","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1397":"1397","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","13